<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-515-652  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 515 652.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 p59(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Adding systems to a quality mix. (Alliant Health System hospitalinformation systems)(includes profile of Alliant Health System VPof corporate information systems Parry LaGro)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilder, Clinton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Alliant Health Systems is implementing new information systems toautomate the flow of patient data in its hospitals with the goalof improving the quality of patient care.andP;  Traditional hospitalinformation systems address only patient billing, trackingmedications, procedures, types of illnesses and duration ofhospital stays from a cost/billing perspective.andP;  Alliantinformation services (IS) head Parry LaGro argues that a newapproach to IS can improve quality measurement through integrationwith health care management.andP;  Alliant has flattened its managementstructure and formed work-group teams to make decisions.andP;  A newvice-president oversees quality management, and the 50-memberAlliant IS staff focuses on the requirements of both clinical andaccounting-system clients.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Alliant Health Systems (automation).andO;Topic:     Hospital Information SystemsHealth CareComputer industryCase Study.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>